Welcome to the=C2=A02,810=C2=A0newly Not Boring people=C2=A0who have joined=
 us since last Monday! If you haven=E2=80=99t subscribed, join=C2=A0170,734=
 smart, curious folks by subscribing here:=20
(I will try my best to record an audio version; I was editing down to the w=
ire and I=E2=80=99m fried!)
Today=E2=80=99s Not Boring is brought to you by=E2=80=A6 Masterworks [ http=
s://substack.com/redirect/ac62bd63-07d7-4556-906b-9d50a3b3744c?r=3D9p0gt ]
You may have missed a big financial story earlier this month (Not FTX).=C2=
=A0On the same day that the Dow fell over 600 points, and Bitcoin plunged t=
o its lowest level since 2020; the art market soared.
With the sale of Microsoft Co-founder Paul Allen's art collection, buyers p=
urchased a record $1.6 billion worth of art in less than 24 hours.=C2=A0The=
 super-wealthy see art as a safe investment amid a tumultuous and uncertain=
 global economy, per BBC.
Three things to know about the asset class: 1) fine art can help protect pu=
rchasing power when inflation is high (Goldman), 2) fine art has a -0.34 co=
rrelation to equities (Citi), and 3) contemporary art has appreciated 13.8%=
 annually on average for the last 26 years.
So why am I telling you this if only the .01% wealthiest people can capital=
ize on this asset class?=C2=A0Well, now you can too, with Masterworks.com [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/ac62bd63-07d7-4556-906b-9d50a3b3744c?r=3D9p0=
gt ], the fractional art investment platform.=C2=A0
All offerings are SEC qualified (see offering circulars on the site), and t=
heir track record is solid so far=E2=80=A6their last three offerings handed=
 members 17.8%, 21.5%, and 33.1% annual net returns, respectively.
Now there are 12 paintings in the Not Boring collection. Want to see what's=
 currently available? You can get priority access right here [ https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/ac62bd63-07d7-4556-906b-9d50a3b3744c?r=3D9p0gt ].=C2=A0
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Monday! This is an essay I=E2=80=99ve been thinking about and working=
 on for a little while =E2=80=93 I quote myself a lot because I=E2=80=99ve =
been unintentionally writing about the theme since the beginning of Not Bor=
ing =E2=80=93 and I=E2=80=99m really excited to share it with you. It=E2=80=
=99s as close to a Theory of Everything as I can come up with to understand=
 the world in 2022.=C2=A0
Once I started thinking about the world this way, I=E2=80=99ve seen it pop =
up everywhere, from politics to energy to AI. Maybe it=E2=80=99s Baader-Mei=
nhof [ https://substack.com/redirect/de483ea5-3718-4367-b334-be7ba7f6fffa?r=
=3D9p0gt ], maybe it=E2=80=99s real.=C2=A0
And as I=E2=80=99ve tried to explain it to people, I=E2=80=99ve realized th=
at I just need to write down as coherent a thesis with as much evidence as =
I can, and open it up to get feedback and pushback. If nothing else, I hope=
 it can be an interesting conversation starter at Thanksgiving dinner on Th=
ursday.
The idea is this: the world oscillates between centralization and decentral=
ization, with progress sloping upward through the turns. We=E2=80=99re appr=
oaching an era of decentralization.
An important note on how you should set expectations going into this piece:=
=C2=A0
You should not read this as a bull case for crypto. While the word =E2=80=
=9Cdecentralization=E2=80=9D is tied to crypto, this piece is broader than =
that. I actually think one of the things I=E2=80=99ve gotten wrong about cr=
ypto is that it=E2=80=99s a symptom of a larger trend towards decentralizat=
ion, not the cause.
You should read it like I=E2=80=99m Charlie Day in that conspiracy theory m=
eme:
I=E2=80=99m pinning things on the board and trying to connect them, althoug=
h unlike Charlie, I will try to poke holes where the connections don=E2=80=
=99t hold.=C2=A0
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.=C2=A0
Decentralization
The first thing you need to understand is that all of our systems are imper=
fect.=C2=A0
The second, which you need to believe as much as understand, is that they=
=E2=80=99re improving.=C2=A0
Churchill=E2=80=99s quip, that democracy is the worst form of government ex=
cept for all of the others that have been tried, can be applied to the mode=
rn best practice for each and every thing we do.=C2=A0
When our descendants look back on our era from a thousand years in the futu=
re, they=E2=80=99ll view the way that we do everything as incredibly, laugh=
ably primitive. Our most advanced technology, best-laid plans, and most res=
ilient forms of organization will be viewed, if they=E2=80=99re discussed a=
t all, as historical artifacts of a time before we knew what the hell we we=
re doing.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CWait wait wait,=E2=80=9D they=E2=80=99ll think-laugh to each other=
, =E2=80=9CThey used to literally type things into =E2=80=98computers=E2=80=
=99? And get this: they found their partners completely randomly based on w=
hoever lived nearby. And when they needed a thing, they found a picture of =
it on the =E2=80=98internet=E2=80=99 and then another person physically bro=
ught it to their house. No no, also, they burned dinosaur bones to get ener=
gy! Wait, just one more: thousands of them worked for the same =E2=80=98com=
pany=E2=80=99 for years because of efficiency or something? And then they j=
ust=E2=80=A6 died.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Think of any example of a Thing That Just Is, and play it back to yourself =
in those future kids=E2=80=99 voices. It all crumbles under their sneers.=
=C2=A0
Zooming that far out provides a useful perspective. It=E2=80=99s a little e=
asier to accept that the things we hold true will change on that timescale.=
 On a thousand year timescale, it=E2=80=99s much harder to imagine what won=
=E2=80=99t change dramatically. And if history is a guide, it=E2=80=99s har=
d to imagine that things won=E2=80=99t change for the better. The inconsequ=
ential things will fade away. The important things will improve. New will r=
eplace old, as it always does.=C2=A0
What the better versions of everything will look like is a complete unknown=
=2E But the process by which they=E2=80=99=
ll improve, at least in the near fu=
ture, is knowable, at least if we can extrapolate from how things have chan=
ged and improved in the past.=C2=A0
One way to look at the history of the world is as a sine wave oscillating b=
etween centralization and decentralization, with an upward slope on the qua=
lity axis.
To make this idea more tangible, think of what we do for work. Two centurie=
s ago, 84% of Americans worked on (mainly) our own farms in order to feed o=
urselves (decentralized, inefficient). By a century ago, we worked for a bo=
ss in big factories (centralized, more efficient), and today, while many pe=
ople still work inside of big companies, more and more of us are working fo=
r ourselves or in creative jobs while automation replaces evermore of what =
humans used to do (decentralized, even more efficient). Technological innov=
ation enabled that progress =E2=80=93 first, the Industrial Revolution=E2=
=80=99s steam engines, then the Internet.=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s this excellent 2013 Slate Star Codex post, We Wrestle Not W=
ith Flesh and Blood, But Against Powers and Principalities [ https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/667af61d-6bde-4122-a37b-664b983c25c0?r=3D9p0gt ], in which =
SSC describes Puppets and Vast Formless Things (terms he borrows from Edgar=
 Allan Poe=E2=80=99s Ligaea). Vast Formless Things are the drivers of chang=
e in history. Puppets are the interchangeable people or institutions that c=
arry out the bidding of the Vast Formless Things.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CI think,=E2=80=9D writes SSC, =E2=80=9Cthe vastest and most formle=
ss Vast Formless Thing of all is technological progress.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
As an example, he argues that the Printing Press precipitated the Protestan=
t Reformation, the Newspaper, the Renaissance, the Scientific Revolution, a=
nd the Rise of Nationalism. Martin Luther, Leonardo da Vinci, and Sir Isaac=
 Newton were Puppets. The Printing Press was the Vast Formless Thing. After=
 its invention, all of those other things were destined to happen, no matte=
r who ended up bringing them to life. =E2=80=9CSo the biggest changes in hi=
story have been predetermined reactions to different technological conditio=
ns.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
In this view, technological progress sets the stage, and everything else pl=
ays its scripted part.=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99ve written a lot about technological progress, and my belief that=
 things are only going to get crazier [ https://substack.com/redirect/ac032=
bf2-8cc7-47b7-96e0-9a6d22b7498a?r=3D9p0gt ] from here. I=E2=80=99ve written=
 about progress as an exponential but smooth thing. But it might be more st=
ark than that; technological progress may draw a more clear boundary betwee=
n eras, between the way things were and the way things are going to be.
Right now, as you read this, we=E2=80=99re only really less than thirty yea=
rs into one of the biggest technological changes in history =E2=80=93 the I=
nternet =E2=80=93 and we=E2=80=99re standing on the precipice of a bunch of=
 other big potential driving shifts: AI and renewable energy are two with t=
he potential to really shake things up, among others. If things feel unstab=
le, that=E2=80=99s because they probably are.=C2=A0
The Straussians would say that we=E2=80=99re about to enter our Fourth Turn=
ing [ https://substack.com/redirect/cd33ee5d-9066-44c5-9249-3ad03571ea4a?r=
=3D9p0gt ]. Historically, according to Strauss, Fourth Turnings have been m=
arked by [ https://substack.com/redirect/bcdafac7-3ce2-451a-9185-1c15d8e4cc=
08?r=3D9p0gt ] =E2=80=9Cbone-jarring Crises so monumental that, by their en=
d, American society emerged in a wholly new form.=E2=80=9D The last Fourth =
Turning was kicked off by the stock market crash of 1929 and ended with the=
 end of World War II.=C2=A0
If history repeats itself, we=E2=80=99re on the verge of a twenty year wint=
er set off by a major crisis like a financial crash and global war. Given e=
verything going on in the world, that possibility doesn=E2=80=99t seem so f=
ar-fetched. On the other side, in the next First Turning, a new order await=
s.=C2=A0
In a prescient 2015 blog post, A Big Sweeping Theory of Modern History [ ht=
tps://substack.com/redirect/6a7c4821-84a7-4aff-81fb-cac1b726c446?r=3D9p0gt =
], Noah Smith [ https://substack.com/redirect/fb2effee-c5f6-48a2-b41b-74187=
edfe7e0?r=3D9p0gt ] laid out the cycle slightly differently, but ended up i=
n the same place: war, and then a new order.=C2=A0
More softly and hopefully, we=E2=80=99re in a Liminal Space, =E2=80=9Cneith=
er here nor there.=E2=80=9D My mom recently read How to Lead When You Don=
=E2=80=99t Know Where You=E2=80=99re Going; Leading in a Liminal Season [ h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/946179fc-9f20-4d34-93b0-763333120c4f?r=3D9p0gt=
 ] by Rev. Susan Beaumont, and emailed me her notes. Baader-Meinhof strikes=
 again. According to Beaumont, there are three phases of the change process=
:
Separation: A period in which a person, group or social order is stripped o=
f the identity and status that previously defined it.
Liminal Period: A disorienting period of non-structure or anti-structure th=
at opens new possibilities no longer based on old status or power hierarchi=
es. New identities are explored and new possibilities considered.
Reorientation: A reforming period in which the person, group, or social ord=
er adopts=C2=A0 a new identity, is granted new status and designs new struc=
tures more appropriately suited for the new identity.
Whether we=E2=80=99re entering a Fourth Turning, a major war, living in a L=
iminal Space, or all three, it=E2=80=99s increasingly clear that we=E2=80=
=99re heading towards something new on the other side.=C2=A0
Here=E2=80=99s my working thesis:=C2=A0
We=E2=80=99re heading towards an era of greater decentralization on all fro=
nts =E2=80=93 geopolitics, finance, education, journalism, and energy are j=
ust a few examples =E2=80=93 driven by technologies including, but not limi=
ted to, the internet. This newly decentralized era will require new infrast=
ructure and organizing principles that can adapt to the chaos and complexit=
y inherent in decentralized systems.=C2=A0
My argument isn=E2=80=99t clean or without gaping openings for counter-argu=
ments, and I=E2=80=99ll try to make some of those, too. Again, think Charli=
e Day at that conspiracy board. But everywhere I look, I see the seedlings =
of a shift from centralization to decentralization:
Energy: Fossil Fuels vs. Renewables=C2=A0
Manufacturing: Globalization vs. Reshoring
Manufacturing: Making vs. Growing
Science: Government Funded vs. Decentralized
Hard Tech: Government Agencies & Incumbents vs. Startups
AI: Closed vs. Open
Talent: Big Tech vs. Startups
Apps: Big vs. Small
Media: Substack vs. Journalism
Education: Factory vs. Personalized
Finance: Big Banks vs. Fintech
Don=E2=80=99t worry, we=E2=80=99ll cover all of these in turn.=20
The push towards decentralization isn=E2=80=99t complete. It may just be st=
arting. Even at maturity, there will still certainly be centralized counter=
-examples (and the seeds of re-centralization).
In the middle of this storm, in this Liminal Space, it feels like things ar=
e fragmenting and splintering, directionlessly and pointlessly. But I=E2=80=
=99m an optimist [ https://substack.com/redirect/ee1a4b2c-a29e-4b5a-965f-d7=
53d55d3326?r=3D9p0gt ], and I think there=E2=80=99s an upward slope to all =
of the ups and downs. New technologies shatter old systems, but they help u=
s piece new ones together in previously-impossible and superior ways.=C2=A0
Before we get to those examples, let=E2=80=99s take a journey through the h=
istory of that upward sloping sine wave to set the stage for the idea that =
not only are a bunch of things decentralizing, but that that decentralizati=
on sets the stage for a new era defined by decentralization.
The Upward Sloping Sine Wave
In the beginning, there was nothing. Then, in an instant, total centralizat=
ion. All of the energy and matter in the universe existed in one single sup=
erdense, superhot point. Then=E2=80=A6 bang.=C2=A0
The Big Bang kicked off an ongoing, 13.8 billion year process of universal =
decentralization. The universe continues to expand at a rate of 74 kilomete=
rs per second per megaparsec. That=E2=80=99s really fast. From a single poi=
nt to a 93-billion-light-year-wide universe filled with dark matter and pla=
nets and black holes and asteroids and stars and galaxies and supernovae, a=
t least on our tiny little rock, living beings.=C2=A0
The emergence of those living beings, including you, me, and all of the peo=
ple and animals you know and love, could be viewed as a process of centrali=
zation. As Richard Dawkins writes in The Selfish Gene [ https://substack.co=
m/redirect/d8755d7d-714e-4058-8751-d3a5cedcae45?r=3D9p0gt ]:=C2=A0
Darwin=E2=80=99s theory of evolution by natural selection is satisfying bec=
ause it shows us a way in which simplicity could change into complexity, ho=
w unordered atoms could group themselves into ever more complex patterns un=
til they ended up manufacturing people.
The Big Bang sent a bunch of atoms flying, and some of those atoms found ea=
ch other and teamed up, forming molecules, some of which formed genes, whic=
h mutated and replicated over billions of years to create you and me. On th=
at level, we=E2=80=99re walking embodiments of centralization. On a societa=
l level, though, each of us is an atom.=C2=A0
Each of us represents one node in the larger human system, what Tim Urban c=
alls [ https://substack.com/redirect/ed64eec3-df72-4d81-a6c9-955b19d6fba9?r=
=3D9p0gt ] the =E2=80=9CHuman Colossus.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The better we could communicate on a mass scale, the more our species began=
 to function like a single organism, with humanity=E2=80=99s collective kno=
wledge tower as its brain and each individual human brain like a nerve or a=
 muscle fiber in its body. With the era of mass communication upon us, the =
collective human organism=E2=80=94the Human Colossus=E2=80=94rose into exis=
tence.
Human history can be viewed as a history of the ways that we=E2=80=99ve org=
anized ourselves to meet our basic needs and attempted to progress beyond t=
hem.=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s a lot left to cover here! For more on decentralization, inc=
luding 11 examples, the internet as a centralizing force, and how crypto fi=
ts in:
Thanks to Dan [ https://substack.com/redirect/0af9b665-de73-48c3-a94f-7c76e=
c64b361?r=3D9p0gt ] for editing this beast =E2=80=94 I=E2=80=99m sorry for =
making you read so many words.
That=E2=80=99s all for today. Hope you have a great Thanksgiving if you cel=
ebrate, and hope you enjoy all the Americans being offline for a little bit=
 if you don=E2=80=99t! We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox next Monday morn=
ing.=20
Thanks for reading,
Packy

