</figcaption></figure></div><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; li=
ne-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>To make this idea more tangible=
, think of what we do for work. Two centuries ago, 84% of Americans worked =
on (mainly) our own farms in order to feed ourselves (decentralized, ineffi=
cient). By a century ago, we worked for a boss in big factories (centralize=
d, more efficient), and today, while many people still work inside of big c=
ompanies, more and more of us are working for ourselves or in creative jobs=
 while automation replaces evermore of what humans used to do (decentralize=
d, even more efficient). </span><strong>Technological innovation enabled th=
at progress</strong><span> &#8211; first, the Industrial Revolution&#8217;s=
 steam engines, then the Internet.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #4040=
40; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>There&#8=
217;s this excellent 2013 Slate Star Codex post, </span><em><a href=3D"http=
s://substack.com/redirect/667af61d-6bde-4122-a37b-664b983c25c0?r=3D9p0gt" r=
el=3D"" style=3D"color: #404040; text-decoration: underline;">We Wrestle No=
t With Flesh and Blood, But Against Powers and Principalities</a><span>,</s=
pan></em><span> in which SSC describes Puppets and Vast Formless Things (te=
rms he borrows from Edgar Allan Poe&#8217;s </span><em>Ligaea)</em><span>. =
Vast Formless Things are the drivers of change in history. Puppets are the =
interchangeable people or institutions that carry out the bidding of the Va=
st Formless Things.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: =
16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>&#8220;I think,&#8221; =
writes SSC, &#8220;</span><strong>the vastest and most formless Vast Formle=
ss Thing of all is technological progress.</strong><span>&#8221;&#160;</spa=
n></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margi=
n: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>As an example, he argues that the </span><strong>Prin=
ting Press</strong><span> precipitated the Protestant Reformation, the News=
paper, the Renaissance, the Scientific Revolution, and the Rise of National=
ism. Martin Luther, Leonardo da Vinci, and Sir Isaac Newton were Puppets. T=
he Printing Press was the Vast Formless Thing. After its invention, all of =
those other things were destined to happen, no matter who ended up bringing=
 them to life. &#8220;</span><strong>So the biggest changes in history have=
 been predetermined reactions to different technological conditions.</stron=
g><span>&#8221;&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px=
; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">In this view, technological progr=
ess sets the stage, and everything else plays its scripted part.&#160;</p><=
p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 =
20px 0;"><span>I&#8217;ve written a lot about technological progress, and m=
y belief that </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/ac032bf2-8cc7=
-47b7-96e0-9a6d22b7498a?r=3D9p0gt" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #404040; text-d=
ecoration: underline;">things are only going to get crazier</a><span> from =
here. I&#8217;ve written about progress as an exponential but smooth thing.=
 But it might be more stark than that; technological progress may draw a mo=
re clear boundary between eras, between </span><em>the way things were</em>=
<span> and </span><em>the way things are going to be</em><span>.</span></p>=
<p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">Right now, as you read this, we&#8217;re only really less than th=
irty years into one of the biggest technological changes in history &#8211;=
 the Internet &#8211; and we&#8217;re standing on the precipice of a bunch =
of other big potential driving shifts: AI and renewable energy are two with=
 the potential to really shake things up, among others. If things feel unst=
able, that&#8217;s because they probably are.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: #=
404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>The =
Straussians would say that we&#8217;re about to enter our </span><em><a hre=
f=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/cd33ee5d-9066-44c5-9249-3ad03571ea4a?r=
=3D9p0gt" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #404040; text-decoration: underline;">Fo=
urth Turning</a></em><span>. Historically, according to Strauss, Fourth Tur=
nings </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/bcdafac7-3ce2-451a-91=
85-1c15d8e4cc08?r=3D9p0gt" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #404040; text-decoratio=
n: underline;">have been marked by</a><span> &#8220;bone-jarring Crises so =
monumental that, by their end, American society emerged in a wholly new for=
m.&#8221; The last Fourth Turning was kicked off by the stock market crash =
of 1929 and ended with the end of World War II.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D=
"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">I=
f history repeats itself, we&#8217;re on the verge of a twenty year winter =
set off by a major crisis like a financial crash and global war. Given ever=
ything going on in the world, that possibility doesn&#8217;t seem so far-fe=
tched. On the other side, in the next First Turning, a new order awaits.&#1=
60;</p><p style=3D"color: #404040; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; marg=
in: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>In a prescient 2015 blog post, </span><em><a href=3D=
